bmo: Great news: you don’t have to fight html2canvas/dom-to-image anymore. There are client-side, deterministic ways to export a styled snippet that don’t rely on DOM capture at all. Here are novel approaches that work reliably with Mantle/Prism, plus tradeoffs and how to implement them quickly.

Option A — Token-to-SVG (then PNG)
- Idea: Skip DOM capture. Tokenize with Prism, then render an SVG yourself: background rect + one <text> element per line + <tspan> per token with fill colors. Embed JetBrains Mono as a data URL in <style> inside the SVG so fonts render identically everywhere.
- Why it works: SVG is vector and honors inline styles deterministically. No Shadow DOM, pseudo-element, or CSS variable extraction issues. Fonts are bundled.
- Steps:
  1) Tokenize: Prism.tokenize(code, grammar) and flatten to lines/segments (you already have flattenTokensToLines).
  2) Compute layout: lineHeight = round(fontSize * 1.5). For monospaced fonts, character advance = measure or simply charCount * charWidth. You can measure once by drawing a long “M” string to a hidden canvas to infer per-char width.
  3) Color map: Build a tokenType -> color map by temporarily inserting <span class="token …"> into the current theme container (you already do this in buildTokenColorMap).
  4) Build SVG string: 
     - <svg width/height> with a <rect> for background and optional border.
     - <style> that inlines @font-face src: url(data:font/woff2;base64,...) for JetBrains Mono and font-variant-ligatures: none.
     - For each line: <text y={…}><tspan fill={color}>segment</tspan>…</text>. Track x with dx on tspans to avoid recomputing absolute x.
  5) Convert to PNG if needed: new Blob([svg], { type: "image/svg+xml" }) → createImageBitmap → drawImage(canvas) → toBlob/toDataURL → download.
- Pros: Pixel-perfect, crisp at any scale, zero layout flakiness, easy to support 1x/2x/3x. You also get an “Export SVG” for free.
- Cons: Need to embed fonts (one-time cost). If you want line numbers, render another column of text.

Option B — Finish the pure-canvas highlighter (you’ve started this)
- You already tokenize with Prism, compute colors via hidden spans, and draw to a canvas. Make it production-solid by:
  - Use TextMetrics for exact vertical metrics:
    - const m = ctx.measureText("Hg"); lineHeight = (m.actualBoundingBoxAscent + m.actualBoundingBoxDescent) * 1.2 (or your 1.5 multiplier).
  - Disable ligatures so canvas width matches DOM: set font-variant-ligatures: none on the preview and ensure canvas font includes "liga" off (JetBrains Mono supports ligatures; disable them for deterministic widths).
  - Tab handling: replace tabs with fixed spaces (e.g., 2 or 4).
  - Emoji/Color fonts: If you care, draw them as-is; most modern canvases handle them fine. Otherwise, strip or replace.
  - Anti-aliasing/scale: You already support scale; set canvas.width/height in device pixels and style width/height in CSS for display (if you ever preview the canvas).
  - Line numbers: Paint a gutter first (different bg), then the numbers with reduced opacity, then code.
- Pros: Zero new deps, full control, works offline, fast.
- Cons: More code to maintain than SVG; you’re reimplementing layout.

Option C — Satori + Resvg WASM (JS-only “server-quality” rendering)
- Idea: Use satori (the engine behind Vercel OG images) to turn a React-like tree into an SVG with fonts. Then rasterize the SVG to PNG fully client-side using @resvg/resvg-wasm.
- Steps:
  1) Tokenize with Prism, produce a small React-like tree: a container + flex column of lines + inline <span> for tokens with style={{ color }}.
  2) Load JetBrains Mono TTF/OTF bytes (fetch from public/) and pass to satori({ fonts: [{ name:'JetBrains Mono', data, weight:400, style:'normal' }] }).
  3) satori returns SVG string. Rasterize with resvg-wasm to PNG Uint8Array; create Blob and download.
- Pros: Gorgeous output, robust text shaping/line breaking, consistent fonts. Deterministic across browsers.
- Cons: Adds ~1–2 small deps and a font file; slight bundle cost. Still all client-side.

Option D — SVG foreignObject clone with fully inlined styles
- Idea: Clone your snippet DOM, inline computed styles for all descendants (and ::before/::after), put it as a <foreignObject> inside an SVG, then render to canvas.
- Key is a robust “style serializer” (walk DOM, getComputedStyle for each node, set style attributes, resolve CSS variables to actual values). Also inline @font-face in the SVG.
- Pros: Captures “exact” DOM including complex CSS decorations.
- Cons: More moving parts; must ensure no external resources or they’ll taint the canvas. Harder than A/B.

Option E — Last resort: headless screenshot service (puppeteer-core)
- Spin up a tiny serverless/edge function (Puppeteer) that receives HTML+CSS + your tokenized colors and returns a PNG. Extremely reliable, but requires infra.

My recommendation
- Short term: Finish Option B (you’re 80% there). It keeps everything client-only and will pass Phase 4 quickly. I can wire up: ligature off, precise line metrics, tabs, line numbers, and an “Export SVG” fallback in ~150 LOC.
- Medium term: Add Option A (Token-to-SVG). It gives you perfect crispness and an “Export SVG” feature users will like. You can keep your color map and tokenization code as-is.
- If you want the most polished “library-quality” output and don’t mind deps, Option C (Satori + Resvg) is fantastic.

Tell me which path you prefer (B quick fix vs A SVG-first vs C Satori), and I’ll implement it right away.
